%I A393869 #11 Jun 07 2026 23:22:25
%S A393869 8,9,16,25,27,32,36,40,45,48,49,50,54,56,63,64,72,75,80,81,88,96,98,
%T A393869 99,100,104,108,112,117,121,125,128,135,136,144,147,152,153,160,162,
%U A393869 169,171,175,176,184,189,192,196,200,207,208,216,224,225,232,240,242,243
%N A393869 Numbers k such that A053669(k) < A003557(k).
%C A393869 Let q = A053669(k) be the smallest prime such that gcd(k,q) = 1. Let squarefree kernel rad = A007947 and let m = A003557(k) = k/rad(k). Then k is in this sequence if q < m.
%C A393869 Proper subset of A013929 (nonsquarefree numbers); does not intersect A005117.
%C A393869 Union of A246547 \ {4} and A360765.
%C A393869 {a(n)} \ A001694 = {1, 4}.
%C A393869 Agrees with A388986 for 55 terms; a(56) = 240 is not in A388986.
%C A393869 Terms are such that there exists a number j < k such that rad(k) | gcd(j,k). This is to say that, though rad(k) | j, j has a factor greater than 1 that does not divide k.
%H A393869 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A393869/b393869.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A393869 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A393869/a393869.png">Diagram showing j <= k</a>, n = 1..72, where a number k is a term of this sequence (written at right in red) for which there exists at least one j <= k (highlighted in blue, which appear in row k of A272619) such that gcd(j,k) > 1, rad(j) does not divide k, but rad(k) | j. Green dots also appear in row k of A272619 but in those cases, rad(k) does not divide j.
%H A393869 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A393869/a393869_1.png">Plot j < k at (x,y) = (j,k)</a>, k = 1..1024, such that gcd(j,k) > 1, rad(j) does not divide k, and rad(k) | j. In the plot, j increases toward the right and k increases downward.
%e A393869 Let r = rad(a(n)) and m = A381803(n).
%e A393869 Table of n, a(n), r, and j for select n:
%e A393869      n    a(n)   r   j
%e A393869   ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
%e A393869      1      8    2  {6}
%e A393869      2      9    3  {6}
%e A393869      3     16    2  {6, 10, 12, 14}
%e A393869      4     25    5  {10, 15, 20}
%e A393869      5     27    3  {6, 12, 15, 18, 21, 24}
%e A393869      6     32    2  {6, 10, 12, 14, 18, 20, 22, 24, 26, 28, 30}
%e A393869      7     36    6  {30}
%e A393869      8     40   10  {30}
%e A393869     17     72    6  {30, 42, 60, 66}
%e A393869     35    144    6  {30, 42, 60, 66, ..., 138}
%e A393869     56    240   30  {210}
%e A393869   1331   5184    6  {30, 42, 60, 66, ..., 5178}
%t A393869 rad[x_] := Times @@ FactorInteger[x][[All, 1]]; a053669[x_] := Module[{qx}, qx = 2; While[Divisible[x, qx], qx = NextPrime[qx]]; qx]; Select[Range[250], a053669[#] < #/rad[#] &]
%Y A393869 Cf. A001694, A003557, A005117, A007947, A013929, A053669, A246547, A388986.
%Y A393869 Proper subsets: A052486, A286708, A303606, A360765, A361098, A366250, A366460, A367708, A369150, A383394, A386762, A389864.
